Cyclistic Bike Share

options(repos = c(CRAN = "https://cloud.r-project.org/"))

Programmed and Analyzed by: Michael Gonzalez

Date: 2024

Overview

In 2016, Cyclistic, a bike-share company based in Chicago, launched its bike-sharing program with a fleet of 5,824 bicycles distributed across 692 stations. The program has since grown and become popular among both locals and tourists, offering a flexible and convenient transportation option. Cyclistic distinguishes itself by providing a range of bicycles, including traditional bikes, reclining bikes, hand tricycles, and cargo bikes, making the service inclusive for people with disabilities. The company’s primary focus has been on building brand awareness and attracting a broad consumer base through flexible pricing plans, including single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Cyclistic’s finance team has identified that annual members are significantly more profitable than casual riders, prompting the marketing team to explore strategies to convert casual riders into annual members.

The company’s success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships, which led to the initiation of this project. The project aims to analyze how different user segments-casual riders and annual members-utilize Cyclistic’s bike-sharing service, with the goal of identifying actionable insights that can drive marketing strategies to increase membership conversion rates.

Project Definition

The primary objective of this project is to understand the usage patterns of Cyclistic’s bike-sharing service between two key user segments: casual riders and annual members. By analyzing historical bike trip data, the project seeks to uncover significant differences in how these two groups use the service, with the ultimate goal of informing a new marketing strategy that encourages casual riders to become annual members.

The project is structured around answering three central questions:

How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently? Why would casual riders be motivated to purchase annual memberships? How can digital media be leveraged to influence casual riders to convert to annual members? This analysis will be used to create data-driven recommendations for Cyclistic’s marketing team, ensuring that the proposed strategies are backed by compelling insights and visualizations that can effectively communicate the findings to the company’s executive team.

print_stats <- function(bp_info){
  for(i in 1:length(bp_info$n)) {
    cat("  BoxPlot Category = ",bp_info$names[i], "\n")
    cat("  Upper Whisker: ",bp_info$stats[5, i], "\n")
    cat("  Q3           : ",bp_info$stats[4, i], "\n")
    cat("  Median       : ",bp_info$stats[3, i], "\n")
    cat("  Q1           : ",bp_info$stats[2, i], "\n")
    cat("  Lower Whisker: ",bp_info$stats[1, i], "\n")
    cat("  Q3 - Q1      : ",bp$stats[4, i] - bp_info$stats[2, i], "\n\n")
  }  
}

rides_data <- RidaDataForRV1 %>%
  group_by(member_casual) %>%
  summarise(num_rides = n())

ggplot(rides_data, aes(x = member_casual, y = num_rides, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::comma(num_rides)), vjust = -0.5) +  # Using scales::comma to format labels
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma, limits = c(0, 1000000)) +  # Adjust the upper limit to add more space
  labs(title = "Number of Rides by Member Type",
       x = "Member Type", 
       y = "Number of Rides") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(color = "black", face = "bold"), 
    axis.text.y = element_text(color = "black", face = "bold"),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
  )

Observations:

  • This is the breakdown of the Number of Rides by Customers and Subscribers. It is shown that there are 71,643 Customers and 720,312 Subscribers. By this basic breakdown, it is evident that there are far more Subscribers than Customers in the combined dataset.

rides_data_2019_2020 <- RidaDataForRV1 %>%
  filter(year(started_time) %in% c(2019, 2020)) %>%

rides_data_2019_2020 <- RidaDataForRV1 %>%
  filter(year(started_time) == 2019) %>%  # Filter data for 2019
  mutate(week_of_year = isoweek(started_time),  # Extract ISO week number
         year = year(started_time)) %>%  # Extract the year
  group_by(member_casual, week_of_year, year) %>%
  summarise(num_rides = n(), .groups = 'drop')  # Count the number of rides for each week, member type, and year

# Create the line chart
ggplot(rides_data_2019_2020, aes(x = factor(week_of_year), y = num_rides, color = member_casual, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.2) +  # Line thickness
  geom_point(size = 2) +   # Optional: Add points at each week
  geom_text(data = rides_data_2019_2020 %>% filter(week_of_year %% 5 == 0), 
            aes(label = scales::comma(round(num_rides, 0))), 
            vjust = 1.5, size = 4) + 
  scale_x_discrete(name = "Week of Year") +  # Set x-axis to discrete with label
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +  # Format y-axis labels
  labs(title = "Number of Rides by Week and Member Type (2019)",
       x = "Week of Year", 
       y = "Number of Rides",
       color = "Member Type") +  # Custom legend title
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(color = "black", face = "bold", angle = 0, hjust = 1), 
    axis.text.y = element_text(color = "black", face = "bold"),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)
  )

rides_data_by_station <- RidaDataForRV1 %>%
  group_by(end_station_name) %>%
  summarise(num_rides = n(), .groups = 'drop')  # Count the number of rides per station

# Sort by the number of rides in descending order to have a better visualization

    axis.text.y = element_text(color = "black", face = "bold"),

Conclusion:

  • For this proect I was tasked at the first question which was “How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?” I will be answering each of the three questions in detail.

  • How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently? Annual members use this bike system much more than the customers do. When broken down by the number of rides the annual members had 720,000 rides while the customers only had 71,000. Based on this data alone, it can be concluded that targeting the customers to try and convert them into annual members may not be the best use of resources. While there are customers to go after and convert, they are a small margin in all of the data that was collected.

  • Why would casual riders be motivated to purchase annual memberships? Casual riders would be motivated to purchase memberships because of the cost savings, convience, and for health and fitness. If the user is planning on using the bikes to commute to work then this is an excellent choice to switch to an annual member because the user will be using it on a daily basis. Another reason is for the health and fitness that riding a bike more consistantly brings. Also, Cyclistic brings a convience to people’s daily lives by offering a mode of transportation.

  • How can digital media be leveraged to influence casual riders to convert to annual members? Digital media can be leveraged to influence casual riders to convert to annual members by placing ads in the most used start and end locations. If these customers saw that they could be benefited by switching to an annual membership they would be more inclinded to do so. The start station with the highest number of rides by customer was HQ QR. The end station with the highest number of rides by customer was Streeter Dr & Grand Ave. By placing ads in both of these locations specifically, the customers are more inclinded to switch to an annual membership.
